## Demographics

Alberta holds the fourth-largest francophone population in Canada, trailing behind the provinces of [Quebec](/Quebec), [Ontario](/Ontario), and [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick). It also boasts the largest francophone community in all of [Western Canada](/Western_Canada). According to the comprehensive [2016 Canadian Census](/2016_Canadian_Census), the number of individuals who identified French as their mother tongue within Alberta was recorded at 86,705, constituting 2.1 per cent of the provincial population. This makes French the third most common mother tongue spoken in Alberta, following English and [Tagalog](/Tagalog_language).

A significant characteristic of the Franco-Albertan demographic is their widespread bilingualism. The vast majority of Franco-Albertans are proficient in both English and French. The 2016 census data revealed that only 3,895 respondents (0.1 per cent of Albertans) reported having proficiency exclusively in the French language. More broadly, 264,715 Albertans, representing 6.6 per cent of the population, declared themselves bilingual in English and French. It’s crucial to note, however, that this latter figure encompasses individuals who may speak French as a [second language](/Second_language) without necessarily identifying as ethnically or culturally Franco-Albertan.

The francophone community in Alberta is largely characterized by migration. A substantial portion, approximately 75 per cent, of francophone residents in Alberta were not born within the province. Nearly half of all Franco-Albertans (nearly 50 per cent) relocated to Alberta from other Canadian provinces or territories. A further significant segment, 24 per cent, were born outside of Canada. Among those born internationally, roughly half originated from Africa, 23 per cent from Europe, 15 per cent from other countries within the Americas, and 13 per cent hailed from Asia. This diverse migratory background contributes to the rich tapestry of Franco-Albertan culture.

In terms of ethnic ancestry, the 2016 census indicated that 411,315 Albertans, or 10.5 per cent of the provincial population, reported having partial or full French ancestry. When categorized by ethnic group, French is the sixth most commonly reported ancestry in Alberta, following Canadian, English, German, Scottish, and Irish. This data highlights the deep-seated, albeit sometimes diluted, French heritage present within the broader Albertan population.

