## Communities

### See also: [List of francophone communities in Alberta](/List_of_francophone_communities_in_Alberta)

Communities within Alberta that are officially recognized for their bilingual status and participation in the Alberta Bilingual Municipalities Association.

The overwhelming majority of Franco-Albertans, a striking 72 per cent, are situated within the province's two most populous metropolitan areas: [Greater Edmonton](/Edmonton_metropolitan_region) and the [Calgary Metropolitan Region](/Calgary_metropolitan_region). The Edmonton region alone is home to 39 per cent of all francophone residents in the province, while the Calgary region accounts for 33 per cent. The remaining Franco-Albertans are dispersed across the other diverse regions of Alberta, forming smaller but no less vital communities.

Alberta is home to four municipalities that have officially adopted bilingual status, offering municipal services in both English and French. These municipalities are [Beaumont, Alberta](/Beaumont,_Alberta), [Falher](/Falher), [Legal, Alberta](/Legal,_Alberta), and [Plamondon, Alberta](/Plamondon,_Alberta). In addition to these four, several other communities actively participate in promoting and providing bilingual services. These include [Morinville](/Morinville), [St. Albert, Alberta](/St._Albert,_Alberta), [St. Paul, Alberta](/St._Paul,_Alberta), [Bonnyville](/Bonnyville), and the [Municipal District of Smoky River No. 130](/Municipal_District_of_Smoky_River_No._130). These communities collectively form the Alberta Bilingual Municipalities Association (ABMA), a collaborative body dedicated to fostering and supporting bilingualism within the province. As of 2018, thirteen communities were members of the ABMA, demonstrating a growing commitment to official bilingualism beyond the provincial level.

