## Education

### Elementary and secondary

The right to French language education for minority francophone populations across Canada is a constitutionally protected entitlement, enshrined under section 23 of the [Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms](/Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms). This right is further reinforced within Alberta by section 14 of the province's *Education Act*. Prior to the enactment of these foundational legal instruments, the scope of francophone educational rights in Alberta was considerably more restricted, with most public schools operating predominantly as anglophone institutions.

French language instruction was permitted within Albertan public schools starting in 1896, although its availability was limited and primarily confined to anglophone elementary schools. Following the recommendations of the [Royal Commission on Bilingualism and Biculturalism](/Royal_Commission_on_Bilingualism_and_Biculturalism), Alberta introduced bilingual schools. These programs featured a division of instructional time, with teachers alternating between English and French as the languages of instruction for classes ranging from Grade 3 to Grade 12. While these bilingual programs were accessible to Franco-Albertans, their primary design and intent were geared towards anglophone or already bilingual students. A significant regulatory shift occurred in 1976 with the introduction of Regulation 250/76, which allowed schools to utilize French as an instructional language for up to 80 per cent of the school day. The subsequent enactment of the Charter proved transformative, ultimately leading the province to establish its first two publicly funded francophone schools in 1984. This culminated in the creation of an independent, publicly funded francophone public elementary and secondary school system in 1994, a monumental victory for linguistic minority education.

The province's public francophone schools are currently administered through one of four distinct regional public school boards: the [East Central Francophone Education Region No. 3](/East_Central_Francophone_Education_Region_No._3), the [Northwest Francophone Education Region No. 1](/Northwest_Francophone_Education_Region_No._1), the [Southern Francophone Education Region No. 4](/The_Southern_Francophone_Education_Region_No._4), and the [Greater North Central Francophone Education Region No. 2](/Greater_North_Central_Francophone_Education_Region_No._2). Each of these four public school boards operates as a mixed secular/[separate school](/Separate_school) board, overseeing a network of 42 elementary and secondary schools distributed across 27 different communities. During the 2017–18 academic year, a total of 7,814 students were enrolled in Alberta's public francophone elementary and secondary schools.

### Post-secondary

Alberta does not currently host an independent, stand-alone francophone post-secondary institution. However, the [University of Alberta](/University_of_Alberta) operates as a bilingual institution, offering a range of bachelor's and master's degree programs conducted entirely in the French language at its dedicated [Saint-Jean campus](/University_of_Alberta_Campus_Saint-Jean), located in the [Bonnie Doon](/Bonnie_Doon,_Edmonton) neighborhood of Edmonton. The origins of this campus trace back to 1928 with the establishment of the private francophone educational institution, *Juniorat Saint-Jean*. This institution was later integrated into the University of Alberta in 1977. Complementing the university programs, the Saint-Jean campus also operates a [college](/College_(Canada)) that has been offering two-year diploma programs in French since 2014. In 2018, the Saint-Jean campus reported an enrollment of 842 students.

