## Notable Franco-Albertans

### Religion

*   **[Father Albert Lacombe](/Father_Albert_Lacombe)**: A highly respected Roman Catholic missionary and one of the earliest prominent figures of the Franco-Albertan community. His legacy is honored through the naming of the cities of [Lacombe, Alberta](/Lacombe,_Alberta) and [St. Albert, Alberta](/St._Albert,_Alberta) in his memory.

### Law

*   **[Mary Moreau](/Mary_Moreau)**: Made history as the first Franco-Albertan appointed to the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) on November 6, 2023. She is notably recognized for her pivotal role in securing the right for Albertans to opt for a criminal trial conducted in French, with a French-speaking jury.

### Politics

*   **[Prosper-Edmond Lessard](/Prosper-Edmond_Lessard)**: Served as Alberta's first French-speaking cabinet minister. He was a [Liberal](/Alberta_Liberal_Party) Member of the Legislative Assembly (MLA) for [Pakan](/Pakan_(electoral_district)) from 1909 to 1913 and for [St. Paul](/St._Paul_(provincial_electoral_district)) from 1913 to 1921. He later became a [Senator](/Senate_of_Canada) representing Alberta from 1925 to 1931.

*   **[Wilfrid Gariépy](/Wilfrid_Gari%C3%A9py)**: A foundational figure in Franco-Albertan and Canadian politics. He served as a Liberal MLA for [Beaver River](/Beaver_River_(provincial_electoral_district)) (1913-1921) and held significant provincial portfolios as Alberta's Minister of Municipal Affairs (1917-1918) and Provincial Secretary (1918).

*   **[Jean Léon Côté](/Jean_L%C3%A9on_C%C3%B4t%C3%A9)**: A Liberal MLA who represented [Athabasca](/Athabasca_(Alberta_provincial_electoral_district)) (1909-1913) and later [Grouard](/Grouard_(electoral_district)) (1913-1923).

*   **[Ernest Côté](/Ernest_C%C3%B4t%C3%A9)**: Distinguished himself as a soldier, diplomat, and civil servant.

*   **[Joseph Miville Dechêne](/Joseph_Miville_Dechene)**: Served as a Liberal MLA for Beaver River (1921-1926) and St. Paul (1930-1935). He later transitioned to federal politics, serving as a [Liberal](/Liberal_Party_of_Canada) Member of Parliament (MP) for [Athabaska](/Athabaska_(electoral_district)) from 1940 to 1958.

*   **[Laudas Joly](/Laudas_Joly)**: Began his political career as a [United Farmers](/United_Farmers_of_Alberta) MLA for St. Paul (1921-1930). He later served as a [Social Credit](/Alberta_Social_Credit_Party) MLA for [Bonnyville](/Bonnyville_(provincial_electoral_district)) from 1952 to 1955.

*   **[Joseph Beaudry](/Joseph_Beaudry)**: A Social Credit MLA who represented St. Paul from 1935 to 1952.

*   **[Léo Piquette](/Leo_Piquette)**: Served as an [NDP](/Alberta_New_Democratic_Party) MLA for [Athabasca-Lac La Biche](/Athabasca-Lac_La_Biche) from 1986 to 1989 and was a prominent advocate for francophone minority rights.

*   **[Paul André Joseph Langevin](/Paul_Langevin_(politician))**: Held a seat as a Member of the Legislative Assembly (MLA) for [Lac La Biche-St. Paul](/Lac_La_Biche-St._Paul) from 1993 to 2001, initially as a Liberal and later as a member of the [PC](/Progressive_Conservative_Association_of_Alberta) party.

*   **[Denis Ducharme](/Denis_Ducharme)**: Served as a PC MLA for [Bonnyville-Cold Lake](/Bonnyville-Cold_Lake) from 1997 to 2008.

*   **[Hector Goudreau](/Hector_Goudreau)**: Was a PC MLA for [Dunvegan-Central Peace-Notley](/Dunvegan-Central_Peace-Notley) from 2004 to 2015. He held significant ministerial positions, including Alberta Minister of Tourism, Parks, Recreation and Culture (2006–2008) and Alberta Minister of Municipal Affairs (2008-2011).

*   **[Claudette Tardif](/Claudette_Tardif)**: Served as a Senator for Alberta from 2005 to 2018, initially as a Liberal and later as an independent. She is notable for being a Franco-Albertan of Russian descent.

*   **[Colin Piquette](/Colin_Piquette)**: Son of Léo Piquette, he served as an NDP MLA for [Athabasca-Sturgeon-Redwater](/Athabasca-Sturgeon-Redwater) from 2015 to 2019.

*   **[Marie Renaud](/Marie_Renaud)**: Has been an NDP MLA representing [St. Albert](/St._Albert_(provincial_electoral_district)) since 2015.

*   **[Randy Boissonnault](/Randy_Boissonnault)**: Made history as the first Franco-Albertan federal minister to represent an Alberta riding. He has served as the Liberal MP for [Edmonton Centre](/Edmonton_Centre) (2015–2019; 2021–present). His federal roles include Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Canadian Heritage (2015-2017) and Minister of Tourism and Associate Minister of Finance (October 26, 2021 to present).

*   **[Pierre Poilievre](/Pierre_Poilievre)**: Holds the distinction of being the first Franco-Albertan federal minister. He has been the Conservative MP for [Nepean—Carleton](/Nepean%E2%80%94Carleton_(federal_electoral_district)) since 2004.

### Sports

*   **[Chris Benoît](/Chris_Benoit)**: A professional wrestler. Although born to a French-Canadian family in Montréal, he was raised in Edmonton and based his wrestling career out of Calgary.

*   **[Arthur Boileau](/Arthur_Boileau)**: A former professional runner of French-Canadian descent. He represented Canada in the marathon at the 1984 and 1988 Olympic Games. He was born in Edmonton.

### Art

*   **[Crystal Plamondon](/Crystal_Plamondon)**: A singer and songwriter hailing from [Plamondon, Alberta](/Plamondon,_Alberta).

*   **[Marguerite-A. Primeau](/Marguerite-A._Primeau)**: A writer who primarily wrote in French. She was from [St. Paul, Alberta](/St._Paul,_Alberta) but spent the majority of her writing career in [Vancouver](/Vancouver).

*   **Les Bûcherons**: This duo is known for presenting French-Canadian music and dance performances to audiences across the province.

*   **[Robert Goulet](/Robert_Goulet)**: An American entertainer of French-Canadian parentage who had Franco-Albertan residency. His family migrated from Massachusetts to northern Alberta when he was merely three months old. There were rumors he was seeking Canadian citizenship, but he passed away in 2007 before any such action could be completed.

